<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="59" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,983,1333]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1092,1117]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species could be distinguished from its congeners by: 1) body large, ca. 
<quantity box="[1228,1313,1092,1117]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
; 2) frontal furrow shorter than anteocular furrow; 3) two paired punctures on frontal region; 4) head densely punctate, except a longitudinal impunctate region of 
<quantity box="[583,675,1164,1189]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
width, interspaces between punctures ca. puncture diameter; 5) pronotum bearing dense punctate rows, except a longitudinal impunctate region of 
<quantity box="[1128,1218,1199,1224]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
width, interspaces between rows ca. puncture diameter; 6) mesoscutellum bearing distinct isodiameter meshes; 7) each side of elytra bearing 9–10 rows of punctures; 8) interspaces between punctures on abdomen of 1–2 punctures’ diameter; 9) each basal impression on tergites impunctate and bearing distinctly isodiameter meshes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
